[src:semidefinite-programming/definite-matrix] If two matrices A and B satisfy $B-A\succeq 0,$ we can define a non-strict partial order $B\succeq A$ that is reflexive, antisymmetric, and transitive; It is not a total order, however, as $B-A,$ in general, may be indefinite.
[src:semidefinite-programming/definite-matrix] Also note that $\succeq$ and $\succ$ do not satisfy the usual correspondence of non-strict and strict partial order relations, because $B\succeq A\land B\neq A$ does not imply $B\succ A$ .
