[src:semidefinite-programming/linear-matrix-inequality] Many optimization problems in control theory, system identification and signal processing can be formulated using LMIs.
[src:semidefinite-programming/linear-matrix-inequality] Also LMIs find application in Polynomial Sum-Of-Squares.
[src:semidefinite-programming/linear-matrix-inequality] The prototypical primal and dual semidefinite program is a minimization of a real linear function respectively subject to the primal and dual convex cones governing this LMI.
[src:semidefinite-programming/linear-matrix-inequality] A major breakthrough in convex optimization was the introduction of interior-point methods.
[src:semidefinite-programming/linear-matrix-inequality] These methods were developed in a series of papers and became of true interest in the context of LMI problems in the work of Yurii Nesterov and Arkadi Nemirovski.
[src:semidefinite-programming/second-order-cone-programming] These each define a subspace that is bounded by an inequality based on a second-order polynomial function defined on the optimization variable x ; this can be shown to define a convex cone, hence the name "**second-order cone**".
[src:semidefinite-programming/second-order-cone-programming] By the definition of convex cones, their intersection can also be shown to be a convex cone, although not necessarily one that can be defined by a single second-order inequality.
[src:semidefinite-programming/second-order-cone-programming] See below for a more detailed treatment.
[src:semidefinite-programming/second-order-cone-programming] SOCPs can be solved by interior point methods and in general, can be solved more efficiently than semidefinite programming (SDP) problems.
[src:semidefinite-programming/second-order-cone-programming] Some engineering applications of SOCP include filter design, antenna array weight design, truss design, and grasping force optimization in robotics.
[src:semidefinite-programming/second-order-cone-programming] Applications in quantitative finance include portfolio optimization; some market impact constraints, because they are not linear, cannot be solved by quadratic programming but can be formulated as SOCP problems.
[src:semidefinite-programming/second-order-cone-programming] The second-order cone is also known by the names **quadratic cone**, **ice-cream cone**, or **Lorentz cone**.
