[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] Semidefinite programs are important tools for developing approximation algorithms for NP-hard maximization problems.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] The first approximation algorithm based on an SDP is due to Michel Goemans and David P.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] They studied the max cut problem: Given a graph *G* = (*V*, *E*), output a partition of the vertices *V* so as to maximize the number of edges crossing from one side to the other.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] Unless P = NP, we cannot solve this maximization problem efficiently.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] Solve the SDP (to within an arbitrarily small additive error $\epsilon$ ).
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] *Round* the SDP solution to obtain an approximate solution to the original integer quadratic program.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] This is an SDP because the objective function and constraints are all linear functions of vector inner products.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] Solving the SDP gives a set of unit vectors in $\mathbf {R^{n}}$ ; since the vectors are not required to be collinear, the value of this relaxed program can only be higher than the value of the original quadratic integer program.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] Finally, a rounding procedure is needed to obtain a partition.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] Goemans and Williamson simply choose a uniformly random hyperplane through the origin and divide the vertices according to which side of the hyperplane the corresponding vectors lie.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] Straightforward analysis shows that this procedure achieves an expected *approximation ratio* (performance guarantee) of 0.87856 - ε.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] (The expected value of the cut is the sum over edges of the probability that the edge is cut, which is proportional to the angle $\cos ^{-1}\langle v_{i},v_{j}\rangle$ between the vectors at the endpoints of the edge over $\pi$ .
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] Comparing this probability to $(1-\langle v_{i},v_{j}\rangle )/{2}$ , in expectation the ratio is always at least 0.87856.) Assuming the unique games conjecture, it can be shown that this approximation ratio is essentially optimal.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] Since the original paper of Goemans and Williamson, SDPs have been applied to develop numerous approximation algorithms.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] Subsequently, Prasad Raghavendra has developed a general framework for constraint satisfaction problems based on the unique games conjecture.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] Semidefinite programming has been applied to find approximate solutions to combinatorial optimization problems, such as the solution of the max cut problem with an approximation ratio of 0.87856.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] SDPs are also used in geometry to determine tensegrity graphs, and arise in control theory as LMIs, and in inverse elliptic coefficient problems as convex, non-linear, semidefiniteness constraints.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] It is also widely used in physics to constrain conformal field theories with the conformal bootstrap.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] The **semidefinite feasibility problem** (SDF) is the following decision problem: given an SDP, decide whether it has at least one feasible solution.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] The exact run-time complexity of this problem is unknown (as of 1997).
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] There are several types of algorithms for solving SDPs.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] These algorithms output the value of the SDP up to an additive error $\epsilon$ in time that is polynomial in the program description size and $\log(1/\epsilon )$ .
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] The ellipsoid method is a general method for convex programming, and can be used in particular to solve SDPs.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] Let *L* be the affine subspace of matrices in Sn satisfying the *m* equational constraints; so the SDP can be written as: $\max _{X\in L}\langle C,X\rangle {\text{ subject to }}X\succeq 0$ .
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] Suppose all coefficients in the SDP are rational numbers.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] Let *R* be an explicitly given upper bound on the maximum Frobenius norm of a feasible solution, and *ε>*0 a constant.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] A matrix *X* in Sn is called *ε-deep* if every matrix *Y* in *L* with Frobenius distance at most *ε* from *X* satisfies the feasibility condition $Y\succeq 0$ .
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] The run-time is polynomial in the binary encodings of the inputs and in log(R/*ε*), in the Turing machine model.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] Note that, in general, *R* may be doubly-exponential in *n.* In that case, the run-time guarantee of the ellipsoid method is exponential in *n*.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] But in most applications, *R* is not so huge.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] In these cases, the ellipsoid method is the only known method that guarantees polynomial runtime in the Turing machine model.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] But in practice, its performance is not so good.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] Most codes are based on interior point methods (CSDP, MOSEK, SeDuMi, SDPT3, DSDP, SDPA).
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] These are robust and efficient for general linear SDP problems, but restricted by the fact that the algorithms are second-order methods and need to store and factorize a large (and often dense) matrix.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] Theoretically, the state-of-the-art high-accuracy SDP algorithms are based on this approach.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] First-order methods for conic optimization avoid computing, storing and factorizing a large Hessian matrix and scale to much larger problems than interior point methods, at some cost in accuracy.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] A first-order method is implemented in the Splitting Cone Solver (SCS).
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] Another first-order method is the alternating direction method of multipliers (ADMM).
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] This method requires in every step projection on the cone of semidefinite matrices.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] The code ConicBundle formulates the SDP problem as a nonsmooth optimization problem and solves it by the Spectral Bundle method of nonsmooth optimization.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] This approach is very efficient for a special class of linear SDP problems.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] Algorithms based on Augmented Lagrangian method (PENSDP) are similar in behavior to the interior point methods and can be specialized to some very large scale problems.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] Other algorithms use low-rank information and reformulation of the SDP as a nonlinear programming problem (SDPLR, ManiSDP).
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] Algorithms that solve SDPs approximately have been proposed as well.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] The main goal of such methods is to achieve lower complexity in applications where approximate solutions are sufficient and complexity must be minimal.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] A prominent method that has been used for data detection in multiple-input multiple-output (MIMO) wireless systems is Triangular Approximate SEmidefinite Relaxation (TASER), which operates on the Cholesky decomposition factors of the semidefinite matrix instead of the semidefinite matrix.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] This method calculates approximate solutions for a max-cut-like problem that are often comparable to solutions from exact solvers but in only 10-20 algorithm iterations.
[src:semidefinite-programming/semidefinite-programming] Hazan has developed an approximate algorithm for solving SDPs with the additional constraint that the trace of the variables matrix must be 1.
[src:semidefinite-programming/spectrahedron] In convex geometry, a **spectrahedron** is a shape that can be represented as a linear matrix inequality.
[src:semidefinite-programming/spectrahedron] Alternatively, the set of *n* × *n* positive semidefinite matrices forms a convex cone in **R***n* × *n*, and a spectrahedron is a shape that can be formed by intersecting this cone with an affine subspace.
[src:semidefinite-programming/spectrahedron] Spectrahedra are the feasible regions of semidefinite programs.
[src:semidefinite-programming/spectrahedron] The images of spectrahedra under linear or affine transformations are called *projected spectrahedra* or *spectrahedral shadows*.
[src:semidefinite-programming/spectrahedron] Every spectrahedral shadow is a convex set that is also semialgebraic, but the converse (conjectured to be true until 2017) is false.
[src:semidefinite-programming/spectrahedron] where $\mathbf {S} _{+}^{n}$ is the set of *n* × *n* positive semidefinite matrices and $\operatorname {Tr} (X)$ is the trace of the matrix X .
[src:semidefinite-programming/spectrahedron] The spectraplex is a compact set, and can be thought of as the "semidefinite" analog of the simplex.
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] A **sum-of-squares optimization** program is an optimization problem with a linear cost function and constraints that certain polynomials constructed from the decision variables should be sums of squares.
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] When the maximum degree of the polynomials involved is fixed, sum-of-squares optimization is also known as the **Lasserre hierarchy** of semidefinite programming relaxations.
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] Sum-of-squares optimization techniques have been applied across a variety of areas, including control theory (in particular, for searching for polynomial Lyapunov functions for dynamical systems described by polynomial vector fields), statistics, finance and machine learning.
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] Detailed descriptions of polynomial SOS are available.
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] Quadratic forms can be expressed as $p(x)=x^{T}Qx$ where Q is a symmetric matrix.
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] Similarly, polynomials of degree ≤ 2*d* can be expressed as $p(x)=z(x)^{\mathsf {T}}Qz(x),$ where the vector z contains all monomials of degree $\leq d$ .
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] An important fact is that p is SOS if and only if there exists a symmetric and positive-semidefinite matrix Q such that $p(x)=z(x)^{\mathsf {T}}Qz(x)$ .
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] This provides a connection between SOS polynomials and positive-semidefinite matrices.
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] A sum-of-squares optimization problem is a conic optimization problem with respect to the cone of sum-of-squares polynomials.
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] Here "SOS" represents the class of sum-of-squares (SOS) polynomials.
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] The quantities $u\in \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ are the decision variables.
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] SOS programs can be converted to semidefinite programs (SDPs) using the duality of the SOS polynomial program and a relaxation for constrained polynomial optimization using positive-semidefinite matrices, see the following section.
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] where $p(x):\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R}$ is an *n*-variate polynomial and each $a_{i}(x)$ is an *n*-variate polynomial of degree at most 2*d*.
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] We adopt the convention that $x_{\emptyset }=1$ , so that the constant coefficient can be included in the Gram matrix of a polynomial.
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] where again *C* is a Gram matrix of *p* and ${\textstyle A_{i}}$ is a Gram matrix of ${\textstyle a_{i}}$ .
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] The first constraint ensures that the value of a monomial that appears several times within the matrix is equal throughout the matrix, and is added to make the matrix X respect the same symmetries present in the matrix $x^{\leq d}(x^{\leq d})^{\top }$ .
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] where we have identified the vectors ${\textstyle f_{i}}$ with the coefficients of a polynomial of degree at most d .
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] This gives a sum-of-squares proof that the value ${\textstyle p(x)\geq y_{0}}$ over $A\subset \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] The above can also be extended to regions $A\subset \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ defined by polynomial inequalities.
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] The sum-of-squares hierarchy (SOS hierarchy), also known as the Lasserre hierarchy, is a hierarchy of convex relaxations of increasing power and increasing computational cost.
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] To augment the basic convex program at the ${\textstyle 1}$ st level of the hierarchy to ${\textstyle d}$ -th level, additional variables and constraints are added to the program to have the program consider polynomials of degree at most $2d$ .
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] The SOS hierarchy derives its name from the fact that the value of the objective function at the ${\textstyle d}$ -th level is bounded with a sum-of-squares proof using polynomials of degree at most ${\textstyle 2d}$ via the dual (see "Duality" above).
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] Consequently, any sum-of-squares proof that uses polynomials of degree at most ${\textstyle 2d}$ can be used to bound the objective value, allowing one to prove guarantees on the tightness of the relaxation.
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] In conjunction with a theorem of Berg, this further implies that given sufficiently many rounds, the relaxation becomes arbitrarily tight on any fixed interval.
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] Choosing ${\textstyle c}$ to be the minimum of the objective function over the feasible region, we have the result.
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] When optimizing over a function in ${\textstyle n}$ variables, the ${\textstyle d}$ -th level of the hierarchy can be written as a semidefinite program over ${\textstyle n^{O(d)}}$ variables, and can be solved in time ${\textstyle n^{O(d)}}$ using the ellipsoid method.
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] A Hermitian polynomial is a function of n complex variables $z_{1},\dots ,z_{n}$ and their conjugates $z_{1}^{*},\dots ,z_{n}^{*}$ which takes on only real values for all complex z .
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] One can also consider semidefinite programming relaxations based on Hermitian sums of squares (HSOS) $g_{1}^{*}g_{1}+\dots +g_{k}^{*}g_{k}$ where each $g_{i}$ is a polynomial in only the variables $z_{1},\dots ,z_{n}$ and not their conjugates.
[src:semidefinite-programming/sum-of-squares-optimization] The resulting semidefinite programs converge to the true optimum asymptotically in all well-behaved cases and reduce to calculating the largest eigenvalues of explicitly given matrices, as first observed by Putinar.
